        "assistant": "Good question — they operate at different levels of the system, and conflating them would dissolve what's distinctive about the token substrate claim.\n\n**Embedding space** is the high-dimensional vector space the model uses internally. Each token gets mapped to a vector, those vectors get transformed layer by layer through attention and MLPs, and the final hidden state is projected back to a distribution over tokens. Embedding space is continuous, dense, and largely opaque — you can't read it without interpretability tools, and the model doesn't operate *on* it in the sense of reading and writing; it's the medium of the forward pass.\n\n**Token substrate**, as defined, is the discrete sequence of tokens in context. It's the surface — what's actually written.\n\nThe key differences for the claim:\n\n1. **Persistence and visibility.** Embeddings are recomputed every forward pass and vanish; tokens persist in context and are visible to the next pass. Cognition that \"lives\" in embeddings is gone the moment the pass ends. Cognition committed to tokens stays.\n\n2. **Movability by writing.** The token substrate claim hinges on the fact that *writing* is the operation that modifies it. You cannot write into embedding space — embeddings are produced by the network, not authored. Tokens, by contrast, are exactly what gets authored, and authoring is what advances cognition.\n\n3. **Identity across passes.** Embedding space is internal to a single forward pass; the token sequence is what carries identity, state, and continuity across passes. If there's a \"thread\" of thought, it lives in tokens, not embeddings.\n\nSo one way to put it: embeddings are where computation happens *within* a pass; tokens are where cognition exists *between and across* passes. The token substrate claim is specifically that the latter — the persistent, writable, visible layer — is the cognitive substrate, not a transcript of one.\n\nA caveat in the spirit of my earlier hedge: this picture treats the weights + per-pass embeddings as mere machinery that re-instantiates cognition from the token state, somewhat like how a Turing machine's tape is the \"real\" state and the head is just a re-applied transition function. That's a defensible framing but not the only one — you could argue the weights encode dispositions that are themselves cognitively substantive, and embeddings carry structure that tokens underdetermine. The token substrate claim is sharper and more committal than that pluralist view.",
