        "user": "How does \"token substrate\" differ from context window?",
        "assistant": "Another good distinguishing question. These are easy to conflate because they refer to nearly the same physical thing — but they're claims at different levels.\n\n**Context window** is an architectural fact: the finite span of tokens the model can attend to in a single forward pass. It's a container, a capacity limit, a technical specification. Saying \"the context window is 200k tokens\" is like saying \"the tape is 200k cells long.\" It describes the resource, not what the resource *is for* or *is made of*.\n\n**Token substrate** is a claim about ontology: what those tokens *are* with respect to cognition. It says the contents of that window aren't data the model processes — they're the stuff thinking is made of.\n\nThe differences:\n\n1. **Container vs. constitution.** Context window names the vessel; token substrate names what fills it and claims that filling is constitutive. You can talk about context windows entirely in engineering terms (tokens, positions, attention cost) without making any claim about cognition. You can't talk about token substrate without making one.\n\n2. **Neutral vs. committal.** \"Context window\" is theory-neutral — a behaviorist, a functionalist, and someone who thinks LLMs don't think at all can all use the term comfortably. \"Token substrate\" takes a position: that cognition is located here, in this discrete writable layer, rather than somewhere deeper or somewhere else.\n\n3. **Passive vs. active framing.** Context window suggests something the model *reads*. Token substrate suggests something the model *is*, or at least something cognition *consists in*. The shift is from \"input\" to \"medium.\"\n\n4. **What gets emphasized.** Context-window framing emphasizes limits — truncation, recency, attention dilution, what falls out. Token-substrate framing emphasizes authorship — that every token written is a modification of the thinking itself, not a note about it.\n\nA compact way to put it: the context window is *where* the token substrate lives, and how much of it can exist at once. The substrate claim is about *what kind of thing* lives there.\n\nThe same caveat applies as before: one can accept \"context window\" as a technical fact while rejecting \"token substrate\" as an ontological claim, and that's a coherent position. The substrate framing earns its keep only if you think the writable, persistent, discrete layer is doing the cognitive work rather than just feeding it.",
