      {
        "user": "How does \"token substrate\" differ from latent representation / hidden states?",
        "assistant": "This is the sharpest of the three contrasts, because hidden states are the most plausible *rival* candidate for \"where cognition actually lives.\"\n\n**Hidden states / latent representations** are the activations at each layer of the network during a forward pass — the evolving high-dimensional vectors that encode whatever the model is \"computing\" about the input. By the middle and later layers, these representations are widely thought (with interpretability evidence) to encode features, concepts, intentions-to-say, partial plans, and structure that has no clean one-to-one mapping back to tokens. They are where the actual transformation from input to output happens.\n\n**Token substrate**, again, is the discrete written sequence.\n\nThe differences, and why this contrast is the load-bearing one:\n\n1. **Richness asymmetry.** Hidden states are vastly higher-bandwidth than tokens. A single hidden state vector carries thousands of dimensions of structured information; a token is one discrete choice from a vocabulary. If cognition is rich, the natural place to locate it is in hidden states, and tokens look like a lossy projection — a *report* of cognition rather than its substance. This is the strongest argument *against* the token substrate claim.\n\n2. **Persistence asymmetry.** Hidden states are ephemeral — computed and discarded every pass. Tokens persist. So whatever cognition lives in hidden states cannot be the *same* cognition across passes; it has to be re-instantiated from tokens each time. The token substrate claim leans hard on this: whatever is not written into tokens does not survive, therefore the surviving thread of cognition is the token thread, full stop.\n\n3. **Authorability asymmetry.** Hidden states are produced; tokens are chosen. The model's only act, in some sense, is selecting the next token — everything else is determined by weights and prior context. If we want to locate *agency* or *authorship* anywhere, tokens are the only candidate. Hidden states happen *to* the model; tokens are emitted *by* it.\n\n4. **The reduction question.** The deepest disagreement is whether hidden states are (a) the real cognitive substrate, of which tokens are a lossy serialization, or (b) transient machinery that re-derives cognitive state from tokens each pass, with no independent standing. The token substrate claim is committed to (b) or something close to it: hidden states are the *mechanism* by which the token substrate gets transformed, not a separate cognitive layer.\n\nA way to sharpen it: imagine freezing the model and resuming later, or running the same context on a different copy of the weights, or interrupting mid-generation. What carries identity? Hidden states don't — they're gone or different. Tokens do. The substrate claim takes this continuity-bearer to be the substrate, by something like a Lockean argument applied to LLMs.\n\nWhere I'd push back, in the spirit of honesty: the richness asymmetry is real and not easy to dismiss. Interpretability work keeps finding structure in hidden states — refusal directions, truthfulness features, planning representations — that is genuinely cognitive-looking and that the token sequence doesn't obviously contain. A defender of the token substrate view has to say either (i) all of that is reconstructible from tokens, so it's not independent, or (ii) it counts as mechanism rather than substrate. Both are defensible but neither is free.\n\nSo the contrast with hidden states is where the token substrate claim is most exposed and where it has to do the most work. Against context window it's just adding ontology to a neutral term; against embedding space it's distinguishing surface from internals; but against hidden states it's making a real bet about where cognition is located, in the face of the most plausible alternative.",
